SECTION 3 — UML ANALYSIS MODEL
3.1 INTRODUCTION
The UML Analysis Model represents the functional behavior of the Pharmacy Management System by
identifying major actors and their corresponding interactions with the system. It serves to illustrate the
functional boundaries, responsibilities, and interactions across various user roles.
The diagrams and narratives in this section are based on the functional requirements outlined in Section 2.4 and
translate them into use-case representations that ensure clarity, completeness, and usability for analysis and
implementation teams.
Each use case is described with its own scope, participating actors, preconditions, postconditions, trigger events,
success scenarios, alternate paths, and exception handling
3.2 ACTORS
3.2.1 POS Cashier (Primary Actor)
The POS Cashier is responsible for executing billing activities, adding medicines to cart, applying discounts,
and processing payments. The cashier interacts with the POS interface to complete customer transactions.
3.2.2 Pharmacist (Secondary Actor)
The Pharmacist performs approval-required activities, such as restricted medicine sale authorizations, reviewing
batch validity, handling returns, conducting stock verifications, and overseeing accurate dispensing.
3.2.3 Store Manager (Supporting Actor)
The Manager is responsible for store operations including inventory oversight, GRN processing, stock
validation, supplier handling, pricing rules, user management, and performance monitoring.
3.2.4 Admin (System Owner Actor)
The Admin manages multi-store setups, master data, global configurations, and cross-store reporting. Admin has
highest level of privileges.
3.2.5 Supplier (External Actor)
The supplier interacts indirectly via PO and GRN workflows. Supplier data is referenced during procurement
and invoice recording.
3.2.6 Customer (External Actor)
The customer is the beneficiary of POS services. Customer details may be captured during billing or
membership registration.
